316 cost to the State if those benefits are kept in trust and are no longer available for paying for
327 the cost of care of children in custody and the cost to the State of administering the trust
338 funds and evaluate whether there is a need for financial literacy training for children with
349 federal benefits in trust funds. The department shall consult with any stakeholders and
450 individuals with relevant expertise. For the purposes of this section, "federal benefit"
461 means a benefit administered by the United States Social Security Administration under
472 Title II of the United States Social Security Act or by the United States Department of
483 Veterans Affairs. The department shall submit a report no later than January 2, 2026 with
494 its findings and any suggested statutory changes necessary to implement a program that
1405 allows children in state custody to retain federal benefits to the Joint Standing Committee
1416 on Health and Human Services. The committee is authorized to report out legislation to
1427 the Second Regular Session of the 132nd Legislature.
13 Sec. 2. Appropriations and allocations. Resolved: That the following
14 appropriations and allocations are made.
15 HEALTH AND HUMAN SERVICES, DEPARTMENT OF
16 State-funded Foster Care/Adoption Assistance 0139
17 Initiative: Provides one-time funding to contract for services to study options for allowing
18 children in the custody of the department to retain certain federal benefits in a special needs
19 trust.
